{
  "doc_id": "40622",
  "text": "In many ways this hierarchical relationship between context and cue mirrors the organization of neural systems across the brain [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Specifically, there has been increasing evidence that higherorder contextual structure might be represented across the prefrontal [CITATION_3] and medial temporal cortices [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . There has also been much work on how the brain supports control over behavior, with emphasis on the role of the anterior cingulate cortex [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] , as well as distributed regions across frontoparietal cortices [CITATION_8] , in particular relation to attentional processes [CITATION_9] . Electrophysiological experiments have demonstrated the importance of slow theta (Θ, 1-7 Hz) oscillations along the frontal midline for both memory maintenance [CITATION_10] as well as control [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] . Additionally, fast gamma ( , > 30 Hz) oscillations across the cortex, and particularly in a frontoparietal system, has been linked to computations driving value-based choice [CITATION_13] , and support the binding between contextual representations and incoming cue-(item) level information [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] ). These findings provide important guidance for delineating the component processes that drive context-dependent choices; however, specifying the potential mechanistic pathways through which these neural systems give rise to behavior remains an important challenge.",
